3 suspects wanted over Bangkok bomb blast | theSundaily
KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian authorities are on the hunt for three more individuals over the bomb blast at Erawan Shrine in Bangkok in August.â€Ž
Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Ahmad Zahid Hamidi said that Malaysian authorities were given three names when they met with the Thai authorities.
"Three names were given to us and we are on the hunt for the individuals," he told reporters on the sidelines of the 10th Asean Ministerial Meeting on Transnational Crime (AMMTC) today.
"However, we need their biometric data and any DNA evidence to speed up the process of their identification and arrests," said Ahmad Zahid who is also Home Minister.
He further pointed out that the suspects could be linked directly or indirectly to the bombing.
"They could have direct involvement with the bomber or they could just have been the taxi driver who brought anyone involved here," he added.
On Sept 23, Deputy Inspector-General of Police Datuk Seri Noor Rashid Ibrahim said four suspects of Uighur ethnicity had been detained over the blast.
They were picked up in the vicinity of of Kuala Lumpur and in Kelantan.
Earlier, Inspector-General of Police Tan Sri Khalid Abu Bakar had announced that a Pakistani man and two Malaysians had been detained to assist in a probe into the bombing.
The blast on Aug 17, claimed the lives of 20 people, including several Malaysians.